<DocsLayout title="Getting started" description="Install etmc, add a relay, and play.">
  <h2>Install</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Install <a href="https://fabricmc.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fabric Loader</a> for Minecraft 1.21.x.</li>
    <li>Drop <a href="https://modrinth.com/mod/fabric-api" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fabric API</a> and the
      <a href="https://github.com/L5Z12/etmc/releases" target="_blank" rel="noopener">etmc jar</a> into your <code>mods/</code> folder.</li>
    <li>Launch the game (Java 21+).</li>
  </ol>
  <p class="muted">etmc also ships for <strong>NeoForge</strong> and <strong>Forge</strong> clients, and a
    <strong>Paper</strong> plugin for dedicated servers — grab the matching jar from
    <a href="https://github.com/L5Z12/etmc/releases" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Releases</a>.</p>

  <h2>Open the menu</h2>
  <p>Press <span class="kbd">G</span> (rebindable under <em>Controls → Misc</em>) or run <code>/etmc menu</code>.</p>

  <h2>Add a relay</h2>
  <p>
    etmc ships no public relay — you provide one. In <strong>Settings</strong>, add an EasyTier node, for example
    <code>tcp://my.relay:11010</code>. The relay coordinates peer discovery and NAT traversal. You can run your own
    EasyTier public node or use one you trust.
  </p>
  <div class="note">No relay = no connections. This is the one piece of setup etmc can't do for you.</div>

  <h2>Play</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Host this world</strong> → pick a network name (+ optional secret) → share the <code>etmc://</code> link or join code.</li>
    <li>Friends paste the <code>etmc://</code> link into <strong>Multiplayer → Add Server</strong>, or use <strong>Join with a code</strong>.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>See <a href="/docs/hosting">Hosting</a> and <a href="/docs/joining">Joining</a> for details.</p>
</DocsLayout>
